        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  To define StructureExtractorError — raised when a structure extractor fails to build a structured document from unstructured input. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  Structure extraction failure error signalling. \par \b Input\/ \:  Error context (msg, filename, version). \par \b Output\/ \:  StructureExtractorError with default HTTP 400 Bad Request code. \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_API(9): <ref refid="classdedoc_1_1common_1_1exceptions_1_1dedoc__error_1_1DedocError" kindref="compound">dedoc.common.exceptions.dedoc_error.DedocError</ref>] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>Uses default code=400 (structure extraction failure often stems from unparseable document content).</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Inherits full DedocError API (msg_api, filename, version, metadata). \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why default code=400 rather than 500? A: A document that cannot be parsed structurally often has invalid or unsupported content — a client data issue, not a server bug. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 — Semantic template markup and LDD logging added.] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CLASS 8[Exception for structure extraction failures] =&gt; StructureExtractorError \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[StructureExtractorError]: StructureExtractor → BuildStructureFailed → RaiseStructureExtractorError → APIResponds400 </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
